# Flex

`TxFlex` is a thin Flexbox primitive for direct control over direction, alignment, wrapping, inline display, and gap. It maps props to CSS variables instead of adding behavior.

## Basic Usage

:::TuffDemoWrapper{demo="FlexFlexDemo" code-lang="vue"}
---
code: |
  <template>
    <div style="width: 360px; padding: 16px; border: 1px solid var(--tx-border-color); border-radius: 12px;">
      <TxFlex justify="space-between" align="center">
        <TxTag label="Left" />
        <TxButton variant="primary">Action</TxButton>
      </TxFlex>
    </div>
  </template>
---
:::

## Composition Examples

### Wrapping Toolbar

```vue
<template>
  <TxFlex align="center" justify="space-between" wrap="wrap" gap="0.75rem">
    <TxFlex align="center" gap="0.5rem" wrap="wrap">
      <TxTag label="Docs" />
      <TxTag label="Reviewed" color="var(--tx-color-success)" />
    </TxFlex>
    <TxButton size="sm">Publish</TxButton>
  </TxFlex>
</template>
```

### Reverse Direction

```vue
<template>
  <TxFlex direction="row-reverse" align="center" gap="8px">
    <TxButton variant="primary">Primary</TxButton>
    <TxButton variant="ghost">Secondary</TxButton>
  </TxFlex>
</template>
```

## Interaction Contract

- The root is a `div` with `display: flex` by default.
- `direction`, `wrap`, `align`, and `justify` are passed directly through to Flexbox CSS variables.
- Numeric `gap` values become px; string values are passed through unchanged.
- `inline=true` switches display from `flex` to `inline-flex`.
- Empty `align`, `justify`, `direction`, or `wrap` values fall back to the component defaults when computed.
- The root sets `min-width: 0` so children can shrink inside constrained cards.

## API

### Props

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `direction` | `'row' \| 'row-reverse' \| 'column' \| 'column-reverse'` | `'row'` | CSS `flex-direction` value. |
| `gap` | `number \| string` | `12` | Gap between children. Numbers become px. |
| `align` | `string` | `'stretch'` | CSS `align-items` value. |
| `justify` | `string` | `'flex-start'` | CSS `justify-content` value. |
| `wrap` | `'nowrap' \| 'wrap' \| 'wrap-reverse'` | `'nowrap'` | CSS `flex-wrap` value. |
| `inline` | `boolean` | `false` | Use `inline-flex` instead of block-level `flex`. |

### Slots

| Slot | Props | Description |
|------|------|-------------|
| `default` | - | Flex children. |

### Events

No public events are emitted.

### Exposed Methods

No public instance methods are exposed.

### CSS Variables

| Variable | Source | Description |
|----------|--------|-------------|
| `--tx-flex-gap` | `gap` | CSS gap. |
| `--tx-flex-align` | `align` | `align-items`. |
| `--tx-flex-justify` | `justify` | `justify-content`. |
| `--tx-flex-direction` | `direction` | `flex-direction`. |
| `--tx-flex-wrap` | `wrap` | `flex-wrap`. |
| `--tx-flex-display` | `inline` | `flex` or `inline-flex`. |

## Best Practices

- Use `TxFlex` when you need exact Flexbox semantics. Use `TxStack` for common horizontal/vertical rhythm.
- Use `wrap="wrap"` on toolbars and filter rows that must survive narrow containers.
- Keep `gap` responsible for spacing; avoid margin hacks on child components.
- Prefer semantic child controls (`TxButton`, links, form controls) inside `TxFlex`; the container itself does not add roles or keyboard behavior.
- For grid-like repeated cards, use `TxGridLayout` instead of nested flex rows.

## Review Notes

- Reviewed against `packages/tuffex/packages/components/src/flex/src/types.ts`, `TxFlex.vue`, and `flex.test.ts`.
- `TxFlex` is intentionally behaviorless: it adds no role, events, or focus handling beyond the slotted children.
- Numeric `gap` is normalized to pixels; string gap values remain caller-owned CSS.

